ral|General]]\n[[File:Vice-Marshal rank insignia (North Korea).svg|25px]] [[Chasu|Vice Marshal]] (promoted July 2012, demoted November 2012) \n|commands     = \n|battles      = \n|education    = \n|mawards      = \n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| hangul    = {{linktext|\ud604|\uc601|\ucca0}}\n| hanja     = {{linktext|\u7384|\u6c38|\u54f2}}\n| rr        = Hyeon Yeongcheol\n| mr        = Hy\u014fn Y\u014fngch'\u014fl\n| koreanipa =\n| context   = north\n| image     =\n| caption   =\n}}\n[[General]] '''Hyon Yong-chol''' ({{korean|hangul=\ud604\uc601\ucca0|context=north}}, 11 January 1949 - c. May 2015<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.kbs.co.kr/news/NewsView.do?SEARCH_NEWS_CODE=3074665&ref=A|title=\ubd81, \uad70 \uc11c\uc5f4 2\uc704 \ud604\uc601\ucca0 \uace0\uc0ac\ucd1d\uc73c\ub85c \uacf5\uac1c \ucc98\ud615|language=Korean|accessdate=2016-10-02|date=2015-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2015/05/13/0200000000AKR20150513084300043.HTML?input=1195m|title=\uad6d\uc815\uc6d0 \"\ud604\uc601\ucca0 \ucc98\ud615 \uc774\uc720\ub294 \uc878\uace0 \uc9c0\uc2dc \ubd88\uc774\ud589\ud55c \ud0d3\"|language=Korean|accessdate=2016-10-02|date=2015-05-13}}</ref>) was a senior [[North Korea]]n [[Military Officer|military officer]] and [[Workers' Party of Korea]] (WPK) politician who served as [[Minister of Defence]] from 2014 to 2015. He was removed from his post and reportedly executed in 2015.<ref name=UPI>{{Cite news|url = http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2015/06/15/North-Korea-officially-confirmed-Hyon-Yong-Chols-execution-says-source/3271434354542|title = North Korea officially confirmed Hyon Yong Chol's execution| date = 15 June 2015|publisher =[[United Press International]]|access-date = 15 June 2015|via = }}</ref><ref name=BBCNews>{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-32716835|title = Hyon Yong-chol, the general who rose out of obscurity|date = 13 May 2015|publisher =[[BBC News]]|access-date = 13 May 2015|via = }}</ref> Although this news was later revealed to be false and Yong-Chol resumed appearing on DPRK state media up to late 2017.<ref>http://www.nkleadershipwatch.org/leadership-biographies/vmar-hyon-yong-chol/</ref>\n\n==Personal life and career==\nNorth Korean media have stated that Hyon was born in January 1949 and joined the military in 1966. Having served as a battalion commander, he was elected a delegate to the Supreme People's Assembly in 2009.<ref name=BBCNews/> Hyon was promoted to the rank of four-star general (\ub300\uc7a5) alongside [[Kim Jong-un]], [[Kim Kyong-hui]], Kim Kyong-ok, [[Choe Ryong-hae]], and [[Choe Pu-il]] in September 2010.<ref name=\"yna\">{{cite news|title=Hyon Yong-chol named vice marshal of N. Korean military|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2012/07/17/41/0401000000AEN20120717005700315F.HTML|accessdate=17 July 2012|newspaper=Yoanhap News Agency|date=17 July 2012}}</ref> He was on the national funeral committee in the wake of [[Kim Jong-il]]'s death in December 2011. Hyon was named as a member of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] at the third party conference.<ref name=BBCNews/> In February 2012, Hyon received the [[Order of Kim Jong-il]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cna.org/CNA_files/PDF/COP-2014-U-006988-Final.pdf#25|page=21|accessdate=11 October 2015|title=North Korean Leadership Dynamics and Decision-making under Kim Jong-un : A Second Year Assessment|first=Ken E.|last=Gause|date=March 2014|publisher=CNA}}</ref>\n\nHyon was promoted to the rank of [[chasu|Vice Marshal]] (\ucc28\uc218) of the [[Korean People's Army|KPA]] in July 2012, two days after [[Chief of the General Staff (North Korea)|Chief of the General Staff]] [[Ri Yong-ho (general)|Ri Yong-ho]] was relieved of his duties. It was initially unclear if Hyon would replace Ri as Chief of the General Staff,<ref>{{cite news|editor=Yang, Lina|title=N Korea names new vice-marshal in military reshuffle|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18865891|accessdate=17 July 2012|publisher=BBC News|date=17 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=DPRK awards Hyon Yong Chol title of KPA vice marshal|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/world/2012-07/17/c_123420259.htm|accessdate=17 July 2012|publisher=[[Xinhuanet]]|date=17 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea promotes military official to key rank after removing army chief|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/07/16/world/asia/north-korea-new-leader/index.html|accessdate=17 July 2012|publisher=CNN|date=17 July 2012}}</ref> but this was confirmed a few days later.<ref>{{cite news|title=DPRK appoints new chief of army general staff|url=http://www.china.org.cn/world/2012-07/19/content_25953916.htm|accessdate=19 July 2012|newspaper=China.org.cn|date=19 July 2012}}</ref> He was also identified as vice-chairman of the WPK Central Military Commission on 26 July 2012.<ref>\"Kim Jong Un Attends Performance by KPISF, Visits Health Complex & Outdoor Ice Rink\", North Korea Leadership Watch, 27 July 2012.</ref>\n\nHyon was reportedly demoted to [[Daejang|General]] in November 2012.<ref>''North Korea Reshuffles 1/3 of Its Military Leadership: Source'', Arirang News, 16 November 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/10/11/2012101100931.html|newspaper=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|title=N.Korean Army Chief Demoted After Defections|date= 11 October 2012}}</ref> On 31 March 2013, Hyon was made a [[Politburo]] alternate member, though he did not take Ri Yong-ho's former seat on the Politburo Presidium.<ref>''Report on Plenary Meeting of WPK Central Committee '', KCNA, 31 March 2013.</ref> He was transferred to command the 5th Army Corps in May 2013.<ref>''N.Korea's Military Reshuffles Are a Dangerous Sign'', The Chosun Ilbo, 24 May 2013.</ref> He was called back to Pyongyang in June 2014 to serve as minister of the People's Armed Forces.\n\n==Ouster and reported execution==\nSouth Korea's [[National Intelligence Service (South Korea)|National Intelligence Service]] initially reported on May 12, 2015, that Hyon was purged and publicly executed near the end of April 2015 at Kanggon Military Training Area near Pyongyang.<ref name=\"North Korea Defence Chief Hyon Yong-chol 'executed'\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-32716749 | title=North Korea Defence Chief Hyon Yong-chol 'executed' | publisher=BBC News | date=13 May 2015 | accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref> It was reported that he was executed \u2013 with a four-barrelled light anti-aircraft gun \u2013 for insubordination and sleeping during formal military rallies, in particular during an event in late April 2015 attended by Kim Jong-un in which Hyon was captured on video napping.<ref name=\"North Korea Defence Chief Hyon Yong-chol 'executed'\"/> A report by [[CNN]] indicated that Hyon was accused of treason after he failed to carry out an order by Kim Jong-un, though the nature of this order was not specified. A top official stated that while executions take place for crimes of treason or subversion, Hyon was not among the executed. According to analysts interviewed by [[BBC News]], while reassigning officials was commonplace in North Korea, the execution of a figure as close to Kim Jong-un as Hyon was surprising, and could give cause to concern for the country's stability.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-13/kim-jong-un-purges-defense-minister-south-korean-lawmaker-says | title=Kim Jong Un Purges Defense Chief for Napping, Lawmaker Says | publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] | accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/05/12/asia/north-korea-defence-ministesr/index.html | title=Reports: North Korea publicly executes defense chief | publisher=[[CNN]]|author1=Kwon, KJ |author2=Whiteman, Hilary | date=13 May 2015 | accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-32716749 | title=North Korea Defence Chief Hyon Yong-chol 'executed' | publisher=BBC| accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nHours after the initial report, South Korea's National Intelligence Service revised its statement, saying that although it has intelligence information suggesting that Hyon was executed, it had not been able to verify that. Doubts were raised because footage of Hyon was still being shown on North Korean television.<ref name=\"purged\">{{cite news|title=North Korea defense chief was purged, maybe not executed, says Seoul's spy agency|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2015/05/13/North-Korea-defense-chief-was-purged-maybe-not-executed-says-Seouls-spy-agency/1931431522581/|date=13 May 2015}}</ref> He was also mentioned in the North Korean newspaper ''[[Rodong Sinmun]]'' the day he was supposed to have been executed. This would imply that he had been arrested and executed on the same day, which is unlikely.<ref>{{cite news|title=Some Doubt That North Korea Executed a Top General|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/14/world/asia/some-doubt-that-north-korea-executed-a-top-general.html?_r=1|author=Choe Sang-hun|publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=13 May 2015}}</ref> On June 16, 2015, confirmation was reported from North Korean diplomatic sources.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2015/06/15/North-Korea-officially-confirmed-Hyon-Yong-Chols-execution-says-source/3271434354542/|title=North Korea officially confirms Hyon Yong Chol's execution|newspaper=UPI|language=en|access-date=2017-02-03}}</ref> In July, official North Korea media named [[Pak Yong-sik]] as the armed forces minister, but did not report Hyon's removal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Seoul: North Korea media confirms purging of defense chief|url=https://news.yahoo.com/seoul-north-korea-media-confirms-purging-defense-chief-030411677.html/|publisher=Yahoo News, AP|accessdate=13 July 2015}}</ref> A South Korean spokesman said that reports of Hyon's execution should be taken as rumors until there was definitive evidence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Defense chief Hyon Yong Chol replaced, confirms Pyongyang|url=http://www.northkoreatimes.com/index.php/sid/234750109|publisher=North Korea Times|date=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Jang Jong-nam]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of People's Armed Forces|Minister of People's Armed Forces]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Pak Yong-sik]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Choe Ryong-hae]]<br>[[Ri Yong-ho (general)|Ri Yong-ho]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Vice Chairman of the [[Central Military Commission (DPRK)|Central Military Commission]]|alongside=[[Choe Ryong-hae]]|years=2012\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Choe Ryong-hae]]}}\n|-\n{{S-mil}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Ri Yong-ho (general)|Ri Yong-ho]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief of the General Staff of the Korean People's Army]]|years=2012\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kim Kyok-sik]]}}\n|-\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hyon, Yong-chol}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:North Korean generals]]\n[[Category:Defence ministers of North Korea]]\n[[Category:People executed for treason against North Korea]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Kim Jong-il]]\n", "text_old": "{{Korean name|Hyon}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix         = [[General of the Army]]\n|name         = Hyon Yong-chol\n|image        =\n|office       = [[Minister of People's Armed Forces|Minister of Defence]]\n|order        = \n|term_start   = 12 June 2014\n|term_end     = 12 May 2015\n|deputy       = \n|predecessor  = [[Jang Jong-nam]]\n|1blankname   = {{nowrap|[[Supreme Leader of North Korea|Supreme Leader]]}}\n|1namedata    = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n|successor    = [[Pak Yong-sik]]\n|office1      = Vice Chairman of the<br /> [[Central Military Commission]]\n|order1       = \n|term_start1  = 26 July 2012\n|term_end1    = 24 May 2013\n|predecessor1 = [[Choe Ryong-hae]] & <br>[[Ri Yong-ho (general)|Ri Yong-ho]]\n|1blankname1  = {{nowrap|[[Supreme Leader of North Korea|Supreme Leader]]}}\n|1namedata1   = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n|successor1   = [[Choe Ryong-hae]]\n|office2      = [[Chief of the General Staff of the Korean People's Army]]\n|order2       = \n|term_start2  = 26 July 2012\n|term_end2    = 24 May 2013\n|predecessor2 = [[Ri Yong-ho (general)|Ri Yong-ho]]\n|1blankname2  = {{nowrap|[[Supreme Leader of North Korea|Supreme Leader]]}}\n|1namedata2   = [[Kim Jong-un]]\n|1blankname3  = {{nowrap|[[Ministry of People's Armed Forces|Defence Minister]]}}\n|1namedata3   = [[Kim Jong-gak]]<br>[[Kim Kyok-sik]]<br>[[Jang Jong-nam]]\n|successor2   = [[Kim Kyok-sik]]\n|birth_name   = Hyon Yong-chol\n|birth_date   = 11 January 1949\n|birth_place  =  [[Kyongsong County|Ky\u014fngs\u014fng County]] (modern [[Orang County|\u014erang County]]), [[North Hamgyong Province]], [[North Korea]]\n|death_date   = c. May 2015\n|death_place  = North Korea\n|religion     = \n|nickname     = \n|allegiance   = {{flag|North Korea}}\n|branch       = [[File:Flag of the Korean People's Army Ground Force.svg|20px]] [[Korean People's Army]]\n|serviceyears = \n|rank         = [[File:General of the Army rank insignia (North Korea).svg|25px]] [[Army general|General]]\n[[File:Vice-Marshal rank insignia (North Korea).svg|25px]] [[Chasu|Vice Marshal]] (promoted July 2012, demoted November 2012) \n|commands     = \n|battles      = \n|education    = \n|mawards      = \n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| hangul    = {{linktext|\ud604|\uc601|\ucca0}}\n| hanja     = {{linktext|\u7384|\u6c38|\u54f2}}\n| rr        = Hyeon Yeongcheol\n| mr        = Hy\u014fn Y\u014fngch'\u014fl\n| koreanipa =\n| context   = north\n| image     =\n| caption   =\n}}\n[[General]] '''Hyon Yong-chol''' ({{korean|hangul=\ud604\uc601\ucca0|context=north}}, 11 January 1949 - c. May 2015<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.kbs.co.kr/news/NewsView.do?SEARCH_NEWS_CODE=3074665&ref=A|title=\ubd81, \uad70 \uc11c\uc5f4 2\uc704 \ud604\uc601\ucca0 \uace0\uc0ac\ucd1d\uc73c\ub85c \uacf5\uac1c \ucc98\ud615|language=Korean|accessdate=2016-10-02|date=2015-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2015/05/13/0200000000AKR20150513084300043.HTML?input=1195m|title=\uad6d\uc815\uc6d0 \"\ud604\uc601\ucca0 \ucc98\ud615 \uc774\uc720\ub294 \uc878\uace0 \uc9c0\uc2dc \ubd88\uc774\ud589\ud55c \ud0d3\"|language=Korean|accessdate=2016-10-02|date=2015-05-13}}</ref>) was a senior [[North Korea]]n [[Military Officer|military officer]] and [[Workers' Party of Korea]] (WPK) politician who served as [[Minister of Defence]] from 2014 to 2015. He was removed from his post and reportedly executed in 2015.<ref name=UPI>{{Cite news|url = http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2015/06/15/North-Korea-officially-confirmed-Hyon-Yong-Chols-execution-says-source/3271434354542|title = North Korea officially confirmed Hyon Yong Chol's execution| date = 15 June 2015|publisher =[[United Press International]]|access-date = 15 June 2015|via = }}</ref><ref name=BBCNews>{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-32716835|title = Hyon Yong-chol, the general who rose out of obscurity|date = 13 May 2015|publisher =[[BBC News]]|access-date = 13 May 2015|via = }}</ref> Although this news was later revealed to be false and Yong-Chol resumed appearing on DPRK state media up to late 2017.<ref>http://www.nkleadershipwatch.org/leadership-biographies/vmar-hyon-yong-chol/</ref>\n\n==Personal life and career==\nNorth Korean media have stated that Hyon was born in January 1949 and joined the military in 1966. Having served as a battalion commander, he was elected a delegate to the Supreme People's Assembly in 2009.<ref name=BBCNews/> Hyon was promoted to the rank of four-star general (\ub300\uc7a5) alongside [[Kim Jong-un]], [[Kim Kyong-hui]], Kim Kyong-ok, [[Choe Ryong-hae]], and [[Choe Pu-il]] in September 2010.<ref name=\"yna\">{{cite news|title=Hyon Yong-chol named vice marshal of N. Korean military|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2012/07/17/41/0401000000AEN20120717005700315F.HTML|accessdate=17 July 2012|newspaper=Yoanhap News Agency|date=17 July 2012}}</ref> He was on the national funeral committee in the wake of [[Kim Jong-il]]'s death in December 2011. Hyon was named as a member of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] at the third party conference.<ref name=BBCNews/> In February 2012, Hyon received the [[Order of Kim Jong-il]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cna.org/CNA_files/PDF/COP-2014-U-006988-Final.pdf#25|page=21|accessdate=11 October 2015|title=North Korean Leadership Dynamics and Decision-making under Kim Jong-un : A Second Year Assessment|first=Ken E.|last=Gause|date=March 2014|publisher=CNA}}</ref>\n\nHyon was promoted to the rank of [[chasu|Vice Marshal]] (\ucc28\uc218) of the [[Korean People's Army|KPA]] in July 2012, two days after [[Chief of the General Staff (North Korea)|Chief of the General Staff]] [[Ri Yong-ho (general)|Ri Yong-ho]] was relieved of his duties. It was initially unclear if Hyon would replace Ri as Chief of the General Staff,<ref>{{cite news|editor=Yang, Lina|title=N Korea names new vice-marshal in military reshuffle|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18865891|accessdate=17 July 2012|publisher=BBC News|date=17 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=DPRK awards Hyon Yong Chol title of KPA vice marshal|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/world/2012-07/17/c_123420259.htm|accessdate=17 July 2012|publisher=[[Xinhuanet]]|date=17 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea promotes military official to key rank after removing army chief|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/07/16/world/asia/north-korea-new-leader/index.html|accessdate=17 July 2012|publisher=CNN|date=17 July 2012}}</ref> but this was confirmed a few days later.<ref>{{cite news|title=DPRK appoints new chief of army general staff|url=http://www.china.org.cn/world/2012-07/19/content_25953916.htm|accessdate=19 July 2012|newspaper=China.org.cn|date=19 July 2012}}</ref> He was also identified as vice-chairman of the WPK Central Military Commission on 26 July 2012.<ref>\"Kim Jong Un Attends Performance by KPISF, Visits Health Complex & Outdoor Ice Rink\", North Korea Leadership Watch, 27 July 2012.</ref>\n\nHyon was reportedly demoted to [[Daejang|General]] in November 2012.<ref>''North Korea Reshuffles 1/3 of Its Military Leadership: Source'', Arirang News, 16 November 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/10/11/2012101100931.html|newspaper=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|title=N.Korean Army Chief Demoted After Defections|date= 11 October 2012}}</ref> On 31 March 2013, Hyon was made a [[Politburo]] alternate member, though he did not take Ri Yong-ho's former seat on the Politburo Presidium.<ref>''Report on Plenary Meeting of WPK Central Committee '', KCNA, 31 March 2013.</ref> He was transferred to command the 5th Army Corps in May 2013.<ref>''N.Korea's Military Reshuffles Are a Dangerous Sign'', The Chosun Ilbo, 24 May 2013.</ref> He was called back to Pyongyang in June 2014 to serve as minister of the People's Armed Forces.\n\n==Ouster and reported execution==\nSouth Korea's [[National Intelligence Service (South Korea)|National Intelligence Service]] initially reported on May 12, 2015, that Hyon was purged and publicly executed near the end of April 2015 at Kanggon Military Training Area near Pyongyang.<ref name=\"North Korea Defence Chief Hyon Yong-chol 'executed'\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-32716749 | title=North Korea Defence Chief Hyon Yong-chol 'executed' | publisher=BBC News | date=13 May 2015 | accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref> It was reported that he was executed \u2013 with a four-barrelled light anti-aircraft gun \u2013 for insubordination and sleeping during formal military rallies, in particular during an event in late April 2015 attended by Kim Jong-un in which Hyon was captured on video napping.<ref name=\"North Korea Defence Chief Hyon Yong-chol 'executed'\"/> A report by [[CNN]] indicated that Hyon was accused of treason after he failed to carry out an order by Kim Jong-un, though the nature of this order was not specified. A top official stated that while executions take place for crimes of treason or subversion, Hyon was not among the executed. According to analysts interviewed by [[BBC News]], while reassigning officials was commonplace in North Korea, the execution of a figure as close to Kim Jong-un as Hyon was surprising, and could give cause to concern for the country's stability.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-13/kim-jong-un-purges-defense-minister-south-korean-lawmaker-says | title=Kim Jong Un Purges Defense Chief for Napping, Lawmaker Says | publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] | accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/05/12/asia/north-korea-defence-ministesr/index.html | title=Reports: North Korea publicly executes defense chief | publisher=[[CNN]]|author1=Kwon, KJ |author2=Whiteman, Hilary | date=13 May 2015 | accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-32716749 | title=North Korea Defence Chief Hyon Yong-chol 'executed' | publisher=BBC| accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nHours after the initial report, South Korea's National Intelligence Service revised its statement, saying that although it has intelligence information suggesting that Hyon was executed, it had not been able to verify that. Doubts were raised because footage of Hyon was still being shown on North Korean television.<ref name=\"purged\">{{cite news|title=North Korea defense chief was purged, maybe not executed, says Seoul's spy agency|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2015/05/13/North-Korea-defense-chief-was-purged-maybe-not-executed-says-Seouls-spy-agency/1931431522581/|date=13 May 2015}}</ref> He was also mentioned in the North Korean newspaper ''[[Rodong Sinmun]]'' the day he was supposed to have been executed. This would imply that he had been arrested and executed on the same day, which is unlikely.<ref>{{cite news|title=Some Doubt That North Korea Executed a Top General|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/14/world/asia/some-doubt-that-north-korea-executed-a-top-general.html?_r=1|author=Choe Sang-hun|publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=13 May 2015}}</ref> On June 16, 2015, confirmation was reported from North Korean diplomatic sources.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2015/06/15/North-Korea-officially-confirmed-Hyon-Yong-Chols-execution-says-source/3271434354542/|title=North Korea officially confirms Hyon Yong Chol's execution|newspaper=UPI|language=en|access-date=2017-02-03}}</ref> In July, official North Korea media named [[Pak Yong-sik]] as the armed forces minister, but did not report Hyon's removal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Seoul: North Korea media confirms purging of defense chief|url=https://news.yahoo.com/seoul-north-korea-media-confirms-purging-defense-chief-030411677.html/|publisher=Yahoo News, AP|accessdate=13 July 2015}}</ref> A South Korean spokesman said that reports of Hyon's execution should be taken as rumors until there was definitive evidence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Defense chief Hyon Yong Chol replaced, confirms Pyongyang|url=http://www.northkoreatimes.com/index.php/sid/234750109|publisher=North Korea Times|date=14 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Jang Jong-nam]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of People's Armed Forces|Minister of People's Armed Forces]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Pak Yong-sik]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Choe Ryong-hae]]<br>[[Ri Yong-ho (general)|Ri Yong-ho]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Vice Chairman of the [[Central Military Commission (DPRK)|Central Military Commission]]|alongside=[[Choe Ryong-hae]]|years=2012\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Choe Ryong-hae]]}}\n|-\n{{S-mil}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Ri Yong-ho (general)|Ri Yong-ho]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief of the General Staff of the Korean People's Army]]|years=2012\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kim Kyok-sik]]}}\n|-\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hyon, Yong-chol}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:North Korean generals]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of North Korea]]\n[[Category:Defence ministers of North Korea]]\n[[Category:People executed for treason against North Korea]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Kim Jong-il]]\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyon_Yong-chol"}
{"title_page": "Juan Jes\u00fas Posadas Ocampo", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Cardinal\n| honorific-prefix = His Eminence\n| name             = Juan Jes\u00fas Posadas Ocampo\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            = [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Guadalajara|Archbishop of Guadalajara]]\n| image            = Cardenal Juan Jes\u00fas Posadas Ocampo.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| church           = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| archdiocese      = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Guadalajara|Guadalajara]]\n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = \n| term_start       = \n| term_end         = 24 May 1993\n| predecessor      = [[Jos\u00e9 Salazar L\u00f3pez]]\n| opposed          = \n| successor        = [[Juan Sandoval \u00cd\u00f1iguez]]\n| other_post       = Cardinal-Priest of Nostra Signora di Guadalupe e San Filippo Martire\n<!---------- Orders\nThe Orders section may be omitted in favour of Template:Ordination for those\nclergy claiming Apostolic succession, such as Catholics, Orthodox and Anglicans. ---------->\n| ordination       = 23 September 1950\n| consecration     = 14 June 1970\n| cardinal         = 28 June 1991\n| created_cardinal_by = [[John Paul II]]\n| rank             = Cardinal-Priest \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|df=yes|1926|11|10}}\n| birth_place      = [[Salvatierra, Guanajuato|Salvatierra]], [[Guanajuato]], [[Mexico]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1993|05|24|1926|11|10}}\n| death_place      = [[Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]], Mexico\n| buried           = \n| nationality      = [[Mexicans|Mexican]]\n| religion         = \n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = <!-- or | partner = -->\n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| previous_post    = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tijuana|Bishop of Tijuana]] <small>(1970-1982)</small><br>[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Cuernavaca|Bishop of Cuernavaca]] <small>(1982-1987)</small>\n| alma_mater       = \n| motto            = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n<!---------- Sainthood ---------->\n| feast_day        = \n| venerated        = \n| saint_title      = \n| beatified_date   = \n| beatified_place  = \n| beatified_by     = \n| canonized_date   = \n| canonized_place  = \n| canonized_by     = \n| attributes       = \n| patronage        = \n| shrine           = \n| suppressed_date  = \n<!---------- Other ---------->\n| other            = \n}}\n\n'''Juan Jes\u00fas Posadas Ocampo''' (11 November 1926 \u2013 24 May 1993) was a Mexican bishop of the Catholic Church who served as the eighth [[archbishop]] of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Guadalajara|see of Guadalajara]] and as a [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal of the Roman Catholic Church]].\n\nPosadas Ocampo was elevated to the cardinalate by Pope [[John Paul II]] on the [[Papal consistory|consistory]] of 28 June 1991.\n\n==Death==\nOn 24 May 1993, Posadas Ocampo, along with six other people, was assassinated in the parking lot of [[Guadalajara International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/25/world/cardinal-in-mexico-killed-in-a-shooting-tied-to-drug-battle.html |title=Cardinal in Mexico Killed in a Shooting Tied to Drug Battle |last=Golden |first=Tim |date=May 25, 1993 |website=World |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> He was inside his car and received 14 [[gunshot]]s. A government inquiry concluded he was caught in a shootout between rival cocaine cartels and was mistakenly identified as a drug lord. According to a cable of the [[Defense Intelligence Agency]], the cardinal was mistaken for [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]],<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. intelligence agency finally releases dispatch on Mexico cardinal assassination at airport|work=Chron|date=14 December 2012|url=http://blog.chron.com/narcoconfidential/2012/12/us-intelligence-finally-releases-dispatch-on-mexico-cardinal-murder/}}</ref> \"El Chapo\", the head of the [[Sinaloa Cartel]]. No one was ever punished for the slaying itself, although charges related to the homicide would be filed. [[Juan Francisco Murillo D\u00edaz]] \"El G\u00fcero Jaibo\" and [[\u00c9dgar Nicol\u00e1s Villegas]] \"El Negro\", members of the [[Tijuana Cartel]], were identified as the masterminds of the homicide.<ref>L\u00f3pez-D\u00f3riga, Joaqu\u00edn. \"Los Agujeros Oscuros en el Asesinato del Cardenal Posadas Ocampo\". ''Radio F\u00f3rmula'', 11 June 2001.</ref>\n\nAlthough ordered by the Tijuana Cartel, many members of the hit squad were actually [[San Diego]]-based members from the Logan Heights gang, trained by the Tijuana Cartel as assassins. Benjam\u00edn Arellano-F\u00e9lix gave up two members of the hit squad: [[Juan Enrique Vasconez]] and [[Ramon Torres Mendez]]. Torres was killed while in custody awaiting trial. Vasconez received 9 years on weapons charges in Mexico.<ref name=\"HistoryChannel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/shows/gangland/episodes/season-4#slide-34|title=Season 4 \u2013 Slide 34|publisher=History Channel|accessdate=14 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nDespite being committed in Mexico, the United States charged 9 members of the Logan Heights hit squad in relation to the murder. Three members ultimately pleaded guilty and received prison sentences of 18\u201322 years.<ref name=\"HistoryChannel\"/>\n\n===Reopening of case===\nThe Posadas case was reopened after president [[Vicente Fox]] won power in 2000, ending seven decades of one-party rule. Fox took office vowing to clear up several high-profile murders. Deputy Attorney General [[Mar\u00eda de la Luz Lima Malvido]] cited serious irregularities in earlier probes, including police obstruction and the disappearance of over 1,000 key documents. Since then, she says she has received death threats \"from powerful quarters\", her teenage daughter was held at gunpoint and her two other children were fired at in their car.\n\nNew leads emerged after the case's opening, including testimony from a childhood friend of Posadas. He says Posadas told him he was summoned to [[President of Mexico|President]] [[Carlos Salinas]]' residence and threatened just weeks before his death. \"There is a lot of proof that leads us to conclude that we are before a crime of state, prepared, organized and with the participation of state security forces,\" Fernando Guzm\u00e1n, a conservative state legislator, said.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} Guzm\u00e1n is close to the investigation because he represented the wife of Posadas' driver, also killed in the attack. He said investigators have ruled out the involvement of drug cartels, at least as the case was presented by Salinas' government. The new theory that the murder may have been ordered by members of the Salinas government was based on allegations that a senior Salinas aide warned Posadas to keep his mouth shut about information he had uncovered linking senior politicians with the drug trade and prostitution. No one has alleged Salinas was personally involved.\n\nAround the 10th anniversary of the killing, senior Church members urged Fox in a letter to keep his word and see the case is solved. Posadas' successor, Cardinal [[Juan Sandoval \u00cd\u00f1iguez|Juan Sandoval]], is convinced the murder was politically motivated. He, his lawyer and Guzm\u00e1n have also reported death threats and appealed to the [[Inter-American Commission of Human Rights]] for protection.\n\nOn 15 August 2006, [[US Department of Justice]] officials announced that US federal drug agents had arrested Mexican drug lord [[Francisco Javier Arellano F\u00e9lix]], a leader of the [[Tijuana Cartel]] responsible for digging elaborate tunnels to smuggle drugs under the U.S. border. In the aforementioned press release, US DOJ officials said Javier Arellano F\u00e9lix was also charged in Mexico in 1993 with conspiring to assassinate Cardinal Juan Posadas Ocampo.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/17/us/17drug.html?_r=1&ref=us&oref=login | work=The New York Times | first1=Jennifer | last1=Steinhauer | first2=James C. | last2=McKinley Jr. | title=U.S. Officials Arrest Suspect in Top Mexican Drug Gang | date=17 August 2006}}</ref>\n\n==In Popular Culture ==\nIn [[Don Winslow]]'s  novel ''[[The Power of the Dog]]'', the character Father Parada is based on parts of Juan Jes\u00fas Cardinal Posadas Ocampo's life and death.\n\nIn [[Netflix]]'s  show ''[[El Chapo (TV series)|El Chapo]]'', Season 1 Episode 4, Cardinal Posadas is assassinated by government conspirators.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people from Morelos, Mexico]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links and additional sources==\n*<small>{{Cite web|last=Cheney |first=David M.|authorlink=|title=Archdiocese of Guadalajara|publisher=[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]|date=|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dguad.html|accessdate=March 25, 2018}} (for Chronology of Bishops)[[Wikipedia:Verifiability#Self-published sources|{{sup|''self-published''}}]]</small>\n*<small>{{Cite web|last=Chow |first=Gabriel|authorlink=|title=Metropolitan Archdiocese of Guadalajara |publisher=[[GCatholic.org]]|date=|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/guad0.htm |accessdate=March 25, 2018}} (for Chronology of Bishops)[[Wikipedia:Verifiability#Self-published sources|{{sup|''self-published''}}]]</small>\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CHRG-109hhrg26906/pdf/CHRG-109hhrg26906.pdf |title=An End to Impunity: Investigating the 1993 Killing of Mexican Archbishop Juan Jesus Posadas Ocampo |date=April 6, 2006 |website= |publisher=U.S. Government Publishing Office |OCLC=70870906}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bposadas.html |title=Juan Jes\u00fas Cardinal Posadas Ocampo |work=Archbishop of Guadalajara, Jalisco, M\u00e9xico |publisher=[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Posadas Ocampo, Juan Jesus}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Salvatierra, Guanajuato]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:Mexican cardinals]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic archbishops of Guadalajara]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Mexican people]]\n[[Category:People murdered by Mexican drug cartels]]\n[[Category:Cardinals created by Pope John Paul II]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mexican murder victims]]\n[[Category:Murdered Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Murdered cardinals]]\n[[Category:May 1993 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic priests]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type             = Cardinal\n| honorific-prefix = His Eminence\n| name             = Juan Jes\u00fas Posadas Ocampo\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title            = [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Guadalajara|Archbishop of Guadalajara]]\n| image            = Cardenal Juan Jes\u00fas Posadas Ocampo.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| church           = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| archdiocese      = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Guadalajara|Guadalajara]]\n| province         = \n| metropolis       = \n| diocese          = \n| see              = \n| term_start       = \n| term_end         = 24 May 1993\n| predecessor      = [[Jos\u00e9 Salazar L\u00f3pez]]\n| opposed          = \n| successor        = [[Juan Sandoval \u00cd\u00f1iguez]]\n| other_post       = Cardinal-Priest of Nostra Signora di Guadalupe e San Filippo Martire\n<!---------- Orders\nThe Orders section may be omitted in favour of Template:Ordination for those\nclergy claiming Apostolic succession, such as Catholics, Orthodox and Anglicans. ---------->\n| ordination       = 23 September 1950\n| consecration     = 14 June 1970\n| cardinal         = 28 June 1991\n| created_cardinal_by = [[John Paul II]]\n| rank             = Cardinal-Priest \n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|df=yes|1926|11|10}}\n| birth_place      = [[Salvatierra, Guanajuato|Salvatierra]], [[Guanajuato]], [[Mexico]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1993|05|24|1926|11|10}}\n| death_place      = [[Guadalajara]], [[Jalisco]], Mexico\n| buried           = \n| nationality      = [[Mexicans|Mexican]]\n| religion         = \n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = <!-- or | partner = -->\n| children         = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| previous_post    = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tijuana|Bishop of Tijuana]] <small>(1970-1982)</small><br>[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Cuernavaca|Bishop of Cuernavaca]] <small>(1982-1987)</small>\n| alma_mater       = \n| motto            = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| coat_of_arms     = \n| coat_of_arms_alt = \n<!---------- Sainthood ---------->\n| feast_day        = \n| venerated        = \n| saint_title      = \n| beatified_date   = \n| beatified_place  = \n| beatified_by     = \n| canonized_date   = \n| canonized_place  = \n| canonized_by     = \n| attributes       = \n| patronage        = \n| shrine           = \n| suppressed_date  = \n<!---------- Other ---------->\n| other            = \n}}\n\n''Juan Jes\u00fas Posadas Ocampo''' (11 November 1926 \u2013 24 May 1993) was a Mexican bishop of the Catholic Church who served as the eighth [[archbishop]] of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Guadalajara|see of Guadalajara]] and as a [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal of the Roman Catholic Church]].\n\nPosadas Ocampo was elevated to the cardinalate by Pope [[John Paul II]] on the [[Papal consistory|consistory]] of 28 June 1991.\n\n==Death==\nOn 24 May 1993, Posadas Ocampo, along with six other people, was assassinated in the parking lot of [[Guadalajara International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/25/world/cardinal-in-mexico-killed-in-a-shooting-tied-to-drug-battle.html |title=Cardinal in Mexico Killed in a Shooting Tied to Drug Battle |last=Golden |first=Tim |date=May 25, 1993 |website=World |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref> He was inside his car and received 14 [[gunshot]]s. A government inquiry concluded he was caught in a shootout between rival cocaine cartels and was mistakenly identified as a drug lord. According to a cable of the [[Defense Intelligence Agency]], the cardinal was mistaken for [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]],<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. intelligence agency finally releases dispatch on Mexico cardinal assassination at airport|work=Chron|date=14 December 2012|url=http://blog.chron.com/narcoconfidential/2012/12/us-intelligence-finally-releases-dispatch-on-mexico-cardinal-murder/}}</ref> \"El Chapo\", the head of the [[Sinaloa Cartel]]. No one was ever punished for the slaying itself, although charges related to the homicide would be filed. [[Juan Francisco Murillo D\u00edaz]] \"El G\u00fcero Jaibo\" and [[\u00c9dgar Nicol\u00e1s Villegas]] \"El Negro\", members of the [[Tijuana Cartel]], were identified as the masterminds of the homicide.<ref>L\u00f3pez-D\u00f3riga, Joaqu\u00edn. \"Los Agujeros Oscuros en el Asesinato del Cardenal Posadas Ocampo\". ''Radio F\u00f3rmula'', 11 June 2001.</ref>\n\nAlthough ordered by the Tijuana Cartel, many members of the hit squad were actually [[San Diego]]-based members from the Logan Heights gang, trained by the Tijuana Cartel as assassins. Benjam\u00edn Arellano-F\u00e9lix gave up two members of the hit squad: [[Juan Enrique Vasconez]] and [[Ramon Torres Mendez]]. Torres was killed while in custody awaiting trial. Vasconez received 9 years on weapons charges in Mexico.<ref name=\"HistoryChannel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/shows/gangland/episodes/season-4#slide-34|title=Season 4 \u2013 Slide 34|publisher=History Channel|accessdate=14 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nDespite being committed in Mexico, the United States charged 9 members of the Logan Heights hit squad in relation to the murder. Three members ultimately pleaded guilty and received prison sentences of 18\u201322 years.<ref name=\"HistoryChannel\"/>\n\n===Reopening of case===\nThe Posadas case was reopened after president [[Vicente Fox]] won power in 2000, ending seven decades of one-party rule. Fox took office vowing to clear up several high-profile murders. Deputy Attorney General [[Mar\u00eda de la Luz Lima Malvido]] cited serious irregularities in earlier probes, including police obstruction and the disappearance of over 1,000 key documents. Since then, she says she has received death threats \"from powerful quarters\", her teenage daughter was held at gunpoint and her two other children were fired at in their car.\n\nNew leads emerged after the case's opening, including testimony from a childhood friend of Posadas. He says Posadas told him he was summoned to [[President of Mexico|President]] [[Carlos Salinas]]' residence and threatened just weeks before his death. \"There is a lot of proof that leads us to conclude that we are before a crime of state, prepared, organized and with the participation of state security forces,\" Fernando Guzm\u00e1n, a conservative state legislator, said.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} Guzm\u00e1n is close to the investigation because he represented the wife of Posadas' driver, also killed in the attack. He said investigators have ruled out the involvement of drug cartels, at least as the case was presented by Salinas' government. The new theory that the murder may have been ordered by members of the Salinas government was based on allegations that a senior Salinas aide warned Posadas to keep his mouth shut about information he had uncovered linking senior politicians with the drug trade and prostitution. No one has alleged Salinas was personally involved.\n\nAround the 10th anniversary of the killing, senior Church members urged Fox in a letter to keep his word and see the case is solved. Posadas' successor, Cardinal [[Juan Sandoval \u00cd\u00f1iguez|Juan Sandoval]], is convinced the murder was politically motivated. He, his lawyer and Guzm\u00e1n have also reported death threats and appealed to the [[Inter-American Commission of Human Rights]] for protection.\n\nOn 15 August 2006, [[US Department of Justice]] officials announced that US federal drug agents had arrested Mexican drug lord [[Francisco Javier Arellano F\u00e9lix]], a leader of the [[Tijuana Cartel]] responsible for digging elaborate tunnels to smuggle drugs under the U.S. border. In the aforementioned press release, US DOJ officials said Javier Arellano F\u00e9lix was also charged in Mexico in 1993 with conspiring to assassinate Cardinal Juan Posadas Ocampo.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/17/us/17drug.html?_r=1&ref=us&oref=login | work=The New York Times | first1=Jennifer | last1=Steinhauer | first2=James C. | last2=McKinley Jr. | title=U.S. Officials Arrest Suspect in Top Mexican Drug Gang | date=17 August 2006}}</ref>\n\n==In Popular Culture ==\nIn [[Don Winslow]]'s  novel ''[[The Power of the Dog]]'', the character Father Parada is based on parts of Juan Jes\u00fas Cardinal Posadas Ocampo's life and death.\n\nIn [[Netflix]]'s  show ''[[El Chapo (TV series)|El Chapo]]'', Season 1 Episode 4, Cardinal Posadas is assassinated by government conspirators.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people from Morelos, Mexico]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links and additional sources==\n*<small>{{Cite web|last=Cheney |first=David M.|authorlink=|title=Archdiocese of Guadalajara|publisher=[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]|date=|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dguad.html|accessdate=March 25, 2018}} (for Chronology of Bishops)[[Wikipedia:Verifiability#Self-published sources|{{sup|''self-published''}}]]</small>\n*<small>{{Cite web|last=Chow |first=Gabriel|authorlink=|title=Metropolitan Archdiocese of Guadalajara |publisher=[[GCatholic.org]]|date=|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/guad0.htm |accessdate=March 25, 2018}} (for Chronology of Bishops)[[Wikipedia:Verifiability#Self-published sources|{{sup|''self-published''}}]]</small>\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CHRG-109hhrg26906/pdf/CHRG-109hhrg26906.pdf |title=An End to Impunity: Investigating the 1993 Killing of Mexican Archbishop Juan Jesus Posadas Ocampo |date=April 6, 2006 |website= |publisher=U.S. Government Publishing Office |OCLC=70870906}}\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bposadas.html |title=Juan Jes\u00fas Cardinal Posadas Ocampo |work=Archbishop of Guadalajara, Jalisco, M\u00e9xico |publisher=[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Posadas Ocampo, Juan Jesus}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Salvatierra, Guanajuato]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:Mexican cardinals]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic archbishops of Guadalajara]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Mexican people]]\n[[Category:People murdered by Mexican drug cartels]]\n[[Category:Cardinals created by Pope John Paul II]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mexican murder victims]]\n[[Category:Murdered Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:Murdered cardinals]]\n[[Category:May 1993 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic priests]]\n", "name_user": "Jkaharper", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juan_Jes%C3%BAs_Posadas_Ocampo"}
{"title_page": "Murder of Jim Pouillon", "text_new": "The '''murder of Jim Pouillon''' occurred on September 11, 2009.  Activist '''James Pouillon''' and businessman '''Michael Fuoss''' were each shot by the same killer, at separate locations.  Pouillon was killed while protesting [[abortion]] in front of Owosso High School in [[Owosso, Michigan]], evidently the first time someone had been murdered while doing so. Police arrested Harlan James Drake and charged him with both crimes. Drake was later convicted of two counts of first-degree murder, and was subsequently sentenced to two life sentences.\n\n==Background==\nJim Pouillon was a well-known Michigan activist and member of [[Operation Save America]].<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite news|title=Police: Shooting suspect offended by anti-abortion material|publisher=CNN|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/CRIME/09/11/michigan.shooting/|date=2009-09-11}}</ref> An elderly man dependent on an oxygen tank to breathe, he had been protesting abortion since 1988.<ref name=cave>{{cite news|author= Damien Cave|title=Memorial Held for Slain Anti-Abortion protester|publisher=New York Times|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/17/us/17abortion.html|date=September 16, 2009|accessdate= August 16, 2012}}</ref> On the day he was shot, Pouillon was leading a protest across the street from Owosso High School in [[Owosso, Michigan]].<ref name=\"cnn\"/>\n\n==Shooting and arrest==\nDuring the protest, Pouillon was shot at 7:20 a.m. [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] by a gunman in a passing vehicle. One witness recorded the vehicle's license plate number. Meanwhile, police were alerted to another murder, of businessman Michael Fuoss at a gravel business he owned. An hour after Pouillon's shooting, police located and arrested the owner of the vehicle, Harlan James Drake. Drake indicated he had shot both victims.<ref name=\"cnn\" />\n\nPouillon's murder was evidently the first time an activist had ever been killed while protesting abortion.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/12/us/12slay.html?em|title=Anti-Abortion Protester Slain in Michigan; Suspect in Custody|work=[[New York Times]]|author=Fitzsimmons, Emma|date=2009-09-11}}</ref> Authorities said Fuoss was not connected to the pro-life movement.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Police said Drake was offended by pro-life material that Pouillon had displayed across from the school for the previous week.<ref name=\"cnn\" /> A [[Center for Reproductive Rights]] spokesperson said the shooting did not seem to be tied to the abortion debate and that Drake was not a pro-choice activist.<ref name=\"nyt\" />  Drake said that he killed Pouillon because Drake and Drake's mother were offended by the fact that Pouillon was displaying a bloody, gory sign near a school where children could see it.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.minbcnews.com/news/story.aspx?id=427345#.VNgOhC6RzIU |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-10-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150102114901/http://www.minbcnews.com/news/story.aspx?id=427345#.VNgOhC6RzIU |archive-date=2015-01-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Trial==\nWhile in custody awaiting trial, Drake attempted suicide by breaking a TV and using the broken glass to cut his wrists.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/09/14/national/main5310255.shtml | work=CBS News | title=Suspect in Mich. Murders Attempts Suicide | date=September 14, 2009}}</ref>  Before the trial, Drake said he shot Pouillon because Drake's mother and nieces were upset by Pouillon's graphic sign, which Drake felt should not be displayed near children.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.minbcnews.com/news/story.aspx?id=427345#.VDjb4lfYyzI |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-10-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150102114901/http://www.minbcnews.com/news/story.aspx?id=427345#.VDjb4lfYyzI |archive-date=2015-01-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  In 2004, Drake was involved \u2014 but not legally responsible \u2014 in a motor-vehicle accident that killed two teenagers. Drake's attorney, Robert Ashley, argued that Drake suffered from [[Major depressive disorder|depression]] stemming from the crash and was therefore mentally incompetent at the time of the murders.<ref>{{cite web|author=The Associated Press |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2010/03/defense_harlan_drake_was_depre.html |title=Defense: Harlan Drake was depressed after 2004 crash that killed two teens |publisher=MLive.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-21}}</ref> On September 30, 2009 Drake was deemed incompetent to stand trial and was remanded into the custody of the Michigan Department of Mental Health.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/01/us/01michigan.html?sq=Pouillon&st=cse&adxnnl=1&scp=7&adxnnlx=1255273248-zNV79sgAEa2ZJShgF72KCA | work=The New York Times | title=Incompetence Ruling in Killing of Abortion Protester | first=Mary M. | last=Chapman | date=October 1, 2009 | accessdate=May 13, 2010}}</ref> Drake was later declared fit to stand trial. Drake testified about how he committed the murder, and even cracked jokes during his testimony.  His testimony proved to be very damaging to his case.<ref>{{cite web|author=Laura Angus | work = Flint Journal |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2010/03/harlan_drake_biggest_witness_a.html |title=Harlan Drake biggest witness against himself in murder trial |publisher=Mlive.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-21}}</ref> On March 11, 2010, the jury returned a verdict of guilty on both counts of first-degree murder.<ref>{{cite web|author=Laura Angus |work =  Flint Journal |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2010/03/harlan_drake_found_xxxx.html |title=Harlan Drake found guilty of first-degree murder in Shiawassee County slayings of pro-life activist, business owner |publisher=Mlive.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-21}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, 2010, Drake received life imprisonment and expressed remorse for the pain caused to the families.<ref>[http://www.freep.com/article/20100423/NEWS06/4230410/1008/Michigan-news-Gunman-gets-life-sentence Detroit Free-Press] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100502235602/http://www.freep.com/article/20100423/NEWS06/4230410/1008/Michigan-news-Gunman-gets-life-sentence |date=May 2, 2010 }}</ref> Drake himself said he should go to jail forever.<ref>{{cite web|author=Laura Angus | work = Flint Journal |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2010/04/harlan_drake_says_he_deserved.html |title=Harlan Drake says he deserved to go to jail 'forever' before sentencing in murder trial |publisher=Mlive.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-21}}</ref>\n\n==Responses==\nSeveral pro-life groups and leaders have deemed Pouillon a martyr.<ref>[http://www.wlns.com/Global/story.asp?S=11116524 WLNS]{{dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS155858+11-Sep-2009+PRN20090911 |title=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |date=2009-09-11 |accessdate=2012-06-21}}</ref> Lori Lamerand, president of Planned Parenthood East Central Michigan, stated the killing was tragic and expressed concerns that people would retaliate.<ref>{{cite web|author=Paul Sancya | agency= AP |url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2009/09/prolife_and_prochoice_leaders.html |title=MLive |publisher=MLive |date= |accessdate=2012-06-21}}</ref> President [[Barack Obama]] has called the killing \"deplorable\" and stated that, \"whichever side of a public debate you're on, violence is never the right answer.\"<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jP2XM0CTfREPoH8eRR16wZ2VMGSgD9AMIOI80 AP] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924074955/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jP2XM0CTfREPoH8eRR16wZ2VMGSgD9AMIOI80 |date=September 24, 2009 }}</ref> Pouillon's funeral was held at the Owosso High School football stadium.<ref name=\"wvcy\">{{cite news|title=In Focus: Jim Pouillon|publisher=[[WVCY-TV]]|url=http://vimeo.com/7366837|date=2009-09-25}}</ref>\n\nPoullion's family gave conflicting descriptions of him. His daughter Mary Jo Pouillon said of him, \"He didn't want to hurt anyone that hadn't hurt him or his family,\" adding, \"They're talking about the babies today. That's what he'd say.\" She sang in a memorial service that drew pro-life activists from across the country.<ref name=cave/><ref>{{cite news|author= Laura Angus|title=Daughter of James Pouillon said she was struck by Harlan Drake's lack of remorse|publisher=mlive.com|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2010/03/daughter_of_james_pouillon_sai.html|date=March 10, 2010|accessdate= August 16, 2012}}</ref> His estranged son Dr. James M. Pouillon wrote, \"It will be impossible for some to believe, but my dad really didn't care about abortion. He did this to stalk, harass, terrorize, scream at, threaten, frighten, and verbally abuse women ... He was at the high school because my niece was there, and female family members were always his favorite targets.\"<ref>[James M. Pouillon criticizes father, slain pro-life activist James L. Pouillon, in online post], ''[[Flint Journal]]'', Laura Angus.September 17, 2009, Updated April 04, 2019. Retrieved April 7, 2020.</ref>\n\nThe right-to-life organization [[Operation Rescue (Kansas)|Operation Rescue]] named Pouillon \"Person of the Year\" for 2009, saying that Pouillon's murder was pro-abortion rights violence.{{Cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Abortion in the United States]]\n*[[United States pro-life movement]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pouillon, Jim}}\n\n[[Category:2009 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:American murder victims]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Michigan]]\n[[Category:2009 in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "The '''murder of Jim Pouillon''' occurred on September 11, 2009.  Activist '''James Pouillon''' and businessman '''Michael Fuoss''' were each shot by the same killer, at separate locations.  Pouillon was killed while protesting [[abortion]] in front of Owosso High School in [[Owosso, Michigan]], evidently the first time someone had been murdered while doing so. Police arrested Harlan James Drake and charged him with both crimes. Drake was later convicted of two counts of first-degree murder, and was subsequently sentenced to two life sentences.\n\n==Background==\nJim Pouillon was a well-known Michigan activist and member of [[Operation Save America]].<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite news|title=Police: Shooting suspect offended by anti-abortion material|publisher=CNN|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/CRIME/09/11/michigan.shooting/|date=2009-09-11}}</ref> An elderly man dependent on an oxygen tank to breathe, he had been protesting abortion since 1988.<ref name=cave>{{cite news|author= Damien Cave|title=Memorial Held for Slain Anti-Abortion protester|publisher=New York Times|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/17/us/17abortion.html|date=September 16, 2009|accessdate= August 16, 2012}}</ref> On the day he was shot, Pouillon was leading a protest across the street from Owosso High School in [[Owosso, Michigan]].<ref name=\"cnn\"/>\n\n==Shooting and arrest==\nDuring the protest, Pouillon was shot at 7:20 a.m. [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]] by a gunman in a passing vehicle. One witness recorded the vehicle's license plate number. Meanwhile, police were alerted to another murder, of businessman Michael Fuoss at a gravel business he owned. An hour after Pouillon's shooting, police located and arrested the owner of the vehicle, Harlan James Drake. Drake indicated he had shot both victims.<ref name=\"cnn\" />\n\nPouillon's murder was evidently the first time an activist had ever been killed while protesting abortion.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/12/us/12slay.html?em|title=Anti-Abortion Protester Slain in Michigan; Suspect in Custody|work=[[New York Times]]|author=Fitzsimmons, Emma|date=2009-09